On 10.0.0.12 right after reboot try

  ntpq -c cv|grep 'timecode="'

and

  ntpq -p | grep '^\*'

and depending on result, use first in rc.local and second in cron.
On 10.0.0.11 do the same, and if not works (due to absence of ntpd
package) - try both `ntpdate -d 10.0.0.12' and `ntpdate -q' in
each case.

----------------

use this in cron?
* * * * * if [ "$(ntpq -np | perl -a -nle print@F[6] | tail -n1)" = "377" ]; then [ -e /tmp/time.blink ] && clock no-blink; else [ -e /tmp/time.blink ] || clock blink; fi 

-----------------

in ConnectBot add entry to show/hide seconds (followed by return):

    if [ -e /tmp/time.no-seconds ]; then clock seconds; else clock no-seconds; fi; exit

and enable "close when connection disappears" in the entry properties
